&lt;h2 id=&#34;installation&#34;&gt;Installation&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you installed Homebrew in the previous step, use it to install NodeJS:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;






&lt;div class=&#34;shell macos&#34;&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;bar&#34;&gt;
  &lt;div class=&#34;controls&#34;&gt;
    &lt;div class=&#34;windows icon&#34;&gt;
      &lt;img src=&#34;http://xternbootcamp17.github.io/images/cmd.png&#34; alt=&#34;&#34;&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&#34;dot red&#34;&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&#34;dot yellow&#34;&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&#34;dot green&#34;&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
  user@localhost ~
  &lt;div class=&#34;windows-controls&#34;&gt;
    &amp;nbsp;
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;shell-body&#34;&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;terminal-commands&#34;
&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;command-line-prompt&#34;&gt;&lt;span data-prompt=&#34;$&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;brew install node
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If not, you can click one of the big, green download links on the Node.js web site.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id=&#34;download-node-js-http-nodejs-org&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://nodejs.org/&#34;&gt;Download Node.js&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;


  &lt;div class=&#34;aside aside-info&#34;&gt;
  
    &lt;h4&gt;Note&lt;/h4&gt;
    
  
  &lt;div class=&#34;body&#34;&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Node version numbers are confusing, but either the LTS version (6.10.2 as of this writing) or the Current version (7.9.0) will so for our puposes.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;h2 id=&#34;testing-your-installation&#34;&gt;Testing your installation&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;After Node is installed, test your installation by running the following command:&lt;/p&gt;








&lt;div class=&#34;shell macos&#34;&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;bar&#34;&gt;
  &lt;div class=&#34;controls&#34;&gt;
    &lt;div class=&#34;windows icon&#34;&gt;
      &lt;img src=&#34;http://xternbootcamp17.github.io/images/cmd.png&#34; alt=&#34;&#34;&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&#34;dot red&#34;&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&#34;dot yellow&#34;&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&#34;dot green&#34;&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
  user@localhost ~
  &lt;div class=&#34;windows-controls&#34;&gt;
    &amp;nbsp;
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;shell-body&#34;&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;terminal-commands&#34;
&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;command-line-prompt&#34;&gt;&lt;span data-prompt=&#34;$&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;npm install -g create-react-app
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You should see a progress bar of sorts while packages download and, eventually, a tree structure of various package names and version numbers. As you may have guessed, aside from testing your Node installation, this has the side effect of installing &lt;code&gt;create-react-app&lt;/code&gt;, which we&amp;rsquo;ll later use to do exactly what its name suggests.&lt;/p&gt;


  &lt;div class=&#34;aside aside-tip&#34;&gt;
  
    &lt;h4&gt;tip&lt;/h4&gt;
  
  &lt;div class=&#34;body&#34;&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;If the &lt;code&gt;npm&lt;/code&gt; command isn&amp;rsquo;t available, open a new tab in your terminal and try again. Opening a new tab should make &lt;code&gt;node&lt;/code&gt; and other related commands available to you from any directory, if they weren&amp;rsquo;t already.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

</description>
